demonstration of the process

00:00:03.316 --> 00:00:05.190
of labeling voltages on a circuit

00:00:05.190 --> 00:00:07.719
that we're about to analyze.

00:00:07.719 --> 00:00:09.957
This is something that
sometimes causes stress,

00:00:09.957 --> 00:00:11.982
or confusion, and I want to just basically

00:00:11.982 --> 00:00:15.299
try to get out of that
stressful situation,

00:00:15.299 --> 00:00:16.798
so the first thing I want to do,

00:00:16.798 --> 00:00:19.548
is remind ourselves of the convention,

00:00:19.548 --> 00:00:22.809
the sign convention
for passive components,

00:00:22.809 --> 00:00:25.957
so we said, If we have a
resistor that we draw this way,

00:00:25.957 --> 00:00:29.935
and we label the voltage
plus or minus V on it,

00:00:29.935 --> 00:00:32.743
then when we label the current arrow,

00:00:32.743 --> 00:00:35.883
we want to label the current arrow

00:00:35.883 --> 00:00:40.098
so it goes into the positive
terminal of the component,

00:00:40.098 --> 00:00:42.456
in this case a resistor,

00:00:42.456 --> 00:00:44.372
so just another quick example,

00:00:44.372 --> 00:00:47.254
if I draw the resistor sideways like this,

00:00:47.254 --> 00:00:50.461
if I label the voltages,
the minus one on this side,

00:00:50.461 --> 00:00:53.083
and the plus one on this side,

00:00:53.083 --> 00:00:56.583
then when I go to apply the current arrow,

00:01:01.210 --> 00:01:04.252
I put the current arrow into
the positive voltage sign,

00:01:04.252 --> 00:01:07.212
so this here is the sign convention

00:01:07.212 --> 00:01:09.158
for an individual component.

00:01:09.158 --> 00:01:10.942
How do we label the voltage,

00:01:10.942 --> 00:01:14.725
and the current together to be consistent?

00:01:14.725 --> 00:01:16.776
Now we're going to to over
and analyze a circuit.

00:01:16.776 --> 00:01:18.460
